# Default constructors
    Imagine you’re joining a new company. On your first day, you receive a welcome kit with a laptop, an ID card, and some basic instructions —
    without asking for it. This "default" setup ensures you’re ready to work, even if no one explicitly customized anything for you.

    Now, consider writing a Java class that represents a student. You want to create multiple student objects, but you don’t always
    have specific data like name or age upfront. You need a way to create these objects quickly and assign initial values later — without repeating code.

    This is where default constructors come in. They offer a predefined setup that helps initialize objects automatically,
    even if no information is provided at the time of creation.

Q1. What Exactly is a Default Constructor? 💡
Standard Definition:
    A default constructor is a constructor with no parameters that is automatically created by the Java compiler if no other constructor is explicitly defined in the class.

# Key Takeaways 📝:

    1. A default constructor is a constructor with no parameters
    2. Java automatically creates it for you if you don’t write any constructor
    3. It allows you to create objects easily, even without passing any data
    4. You can write your own default constructor to set initial values
    5. If you write another constructor (like a parameterized one), Java won’t add the default constructor for you — you’ll need to write it yourself
    6. It’s useful for simple object creation, and it keeps your code clean and flexible

# Common Interview Questions & Answers 💬

    Q1: What is a default constructor in Java?
        It’s a constructor that takes no parameters. If you don’t write any constructor, Java adds one automatically.

    Q2: What happens if I write a parameterized constructor?
        Java stops adding the default constructor for you. You must write it manually if needed.

    Q3: Can I create objects using the default constructor even if I didn’t write one?
        Yes — but only if you didn’t write any other constructor. Java gives you one for free in that case.

    Q4: Why should I use a default constructor?
        To create objects quickly when no values are available yet, or when you want to assign standard values to every object.

    Q5: Can I use both default and parameterized constructors in one class?
        Yes! This is called constructor overloading. It gives you more options for creating objects.